Lessons that can be learned today from the Cuban Crisis
"Thirteen Days" (Dreizehn Tage), a new film about the Cuban Crisis, will soon be released in cinemas of many countries.
Everyone should watch this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events – particularly regarding the controversies surrounding a US national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy convened his closest advisors at the White House.
Air photos of the region had revealed the construction of a station for atomic weapons on Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days, and those that were not reached, could have led to the outbreak of an atomic war.
The film illustrates what happened in the White House during these days.
Audio recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a crucial role in the film's production.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard organized a discussion session to address the film as well as the crisis it examines.
Participants in this round included: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a history professor at Harvard who wrote a book about the "Kennedy-Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a political science professor at Harvard who presented a classic study on the Cuban Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision," thirty years ago.
Additionally, producer Peter A. Almond was present.
Although various points of the filmic treatment of the topic were criticized, the participants in the discussion agreed that the film portrays the problems and the pressure President Kennedy faced exactly as they were in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn from the Cuban Crisis today?
Theodore Sorensen summarized it as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in case of a crisis, but ultimately it is the president who bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – civilian as well as military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions were alternatives and risks revealed that were crucial in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an adversary thinks; moreover, communication lines must remain open.
To isolate an adversary without keeping diplomatic channels open that enable understanding of the opposing situation could prove disastrous.
· The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy acted accordingly because NATO, other allies, and the opinion of the world supported him.
· A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life and death, a politician cannot allow the media to push him into action.
The fact that a week passed during which all involved factors were examined and weighed with great precision was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a margin of time for deliberations still exist today given the existing mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it is necessary to put oneself in the adversary's position.
In one of the most criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade Kennedy imposed on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's resolve, and not as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted more calmly?
After all, the United States had also stationed nuclear warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba merely reflected this policy.
However, Kennedy was anxious about the consequences that a Soviet missile stationing in Cuba regarding Berlin would entail.
The pressure from nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin Crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuban Crisis," as historian Ernest May claimed.
"It will be too late soon," was a widely spread argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to invade Cuba even while they believed the missiles were en route by sea to Cuba.
A troop deployment of about 180,000 U.S. soldiers was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a surprise bombing campaign that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "I needed thirty years," McNamara said, "to discover that there were already nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and 90 of them strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew about it."
And I explicitly recommended that nuclear weapons be used.
I knew this would lead to the annihilation of Cuba."
Castro and, to a greater extent, his comrade Che Guevara were willing to see Cuba vanish in smoke, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
An invasion could thus have led to the deaths of 80 million Americans and the annihilation of Cuba, simply because President Kennedy's administration lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion "certainly" would have led to a Soviet nuclear attack on the USA.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was limited: despite explicit contrary orders, U2 aircraft flying over Cuban airspace were shot down.
A difficult question that did not arise during this debate at Harvard is this: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who distinguished himself during the crisis through rational behavior, but rather an opponent of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of nuclear weapons, this threat could one day become reality.
The discussions today about a limited missile defense and the threat of atomic blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in light of this terrible but decidedly realistic notion.
Harvard has launched a new website on the internet where the key documents about the Cuban Crisis as well as current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
